{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958030601/0130.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\nand continuing\nTHE CHATTAHOOCHEE TRIBUNE\nPublished each Thursday at 15 S. Madison Street\nA lOHN H. PERRI NEWSPAPER\nESTABLISHED 1901\nQuincy, Florida\nEntered in th\u00ae po\u00bbt ottic\u00ae at Quincy Florida, undei th\u00ae Act ot\nMarch ft 1879 a\u00ae matter of the eecond clasv\nOne Year, $3.00 Two Years, $5.50 Six Months, >1.75\nJ. L. Hufhinwii PuMulur\n\u00a9national editorial\nas c 5 t l3 w\nTruman On Recession\nFormer President Harry S. Truman, speaking out on the\nCurrent recession, has offered some interesting advice. In\nthe first place, Truman says that the recession we are now\nencountering is not proof that anything is seriously wrong\nwith our economy.\nMr. Truman believes that we are experiencing a lapse of\nconfidence on the part of the people of the United States, con\nfidence in what we are doing and the economic policies\nbeing pursued by the Administration. Assuming that Mr.\nTruman is not nonpartisan, since he has never been, and\nmaking allowances for that, he is still entitled to his opinion\non the economic state of the Union.\nOn several counts, we think he offers good advice.\nAmong other things that Mr. Truman recommends is less\nemphasis on a balanced budget, expanded welfare services,\nand more effective and greater concentration on the effort\nto attain military security.\nHe reminds us that among the measures which the Eisen\nhower administration adopted to control the economy, and\ncheck inflation, were the raising of interest rates and tight\ncredit control.\nHowever, even after these steps were taken, prices con\n\u00abHnued to rise and unemployment continued to grow, and\nthey obviously did not check inflation. The very economic\nexperts who championed these steps are now, in many\ncases, arguing that they be abandoned and that the govern\nment prime the pump, to prevent a recession.\nMr. Truman charges that vigorous and enlightened lead\nership, and bold decisions, can transform the current pic\nture into one of a growing, expanding, sound economy. He\nhas made a careful analysis of the budget, according to his\nlatest statement, and believes that we should not worry too\nmuch about a balanced budget but should see to it that our\nnational economy is expanded, that we do not let Russia\nstep into a vacuum in various overseas areas, and that we\nrestore the confidence of the people this latter point being\n'.the primary need to improve business.\nMr. Truman is obviously correct on the high interest rates\nand tight credit controls. The high interest rates, especially,\nseem to stifle business expansion, postpone private invest\nment, and fail to accomplish their purpose.\nDo You Read And How?\nCan you read This may seem foolish to you, in view\nOf the fact that you are reading this editorial, but, before\n-\u2022answering, let us consider what it means.\nf An eminent college professor once declared that the\nAmerican people are more than fifty per cent illiterate in\ntheir effective ability to understand adult reading matter. He\nasserted that half the population is unable to read any\nprinted material above the seventh-grade level.\nObviously the educator was telling us that we read care\nlessly, without comprehending the import of the words we\npee. We scan the language without appropriating the\nthoughts and without consciously attempting to absorb the\n^seasonable implications of the words.\nObviously, the nation has millions of citizens who read\n\u2022\u2019carelessly, with resulting confusion as to facts, figures, ratios\nand relationships. The carelessness is apparent in fast and\nslow readers. It relates to a state of mind rather than to\nspeed in reading.\nThere are educators in the United States today who as\nsert that education is largely a matter of acquiring the habit\n-af intelligent reading. The columns of a daily newspaper,\n3br example, take on a new significance if one understands\n*^ie background and implications of events. The same ob\n'^ervation applies to reading, in connection with any subject.\nX We are inclined to agree with the conclusions of the\nCollege professor, but there is no occasion for undue ex\ncitement The human race includes many types of indi\nviduals, with varying interests and degrees of intensity.\nConsequently, wo will always have some good readers,\nsome poor readers, and others utterly unable to comprehend\nthe import of the printed ward.\n3Ln American Plague\nOne of the unbelievable things about our great country\nis that we continue to allow the slaughter of a hundred\ncitizens a day on our highways and city streets. There is\nnothing that can be written about this cancer in our Ameri\ncan way of life that will change the situation overnight.\nz There is little to be written which has not already been\ncovered more eloquently before \u2014by someone else. Never-\ntheless, those charged with the responsibility of writing edi\niorials for the nation's press cannot see the continuing cam\n*Trge on the highways, year after year, with a stilled and\nquiet pen.\nWhat is to be done about the killing, which is more\ndeadly them any war? If we are so emotionally disturbed\n(and rightfully) about the slaughter of mankind in wars, why\nare we less disturbed by equally unjust killings of little\nchildren, boys and girls and adults, by automobiles and\ntrucks, by drunken, careless, or unlicensed drivers?\nNo one answer can be offered as a solution to the great\nAmerican oddity. The only solution lies in a thoroughly\naroused public opinion, which in its wrath, will finally de\nmand that adequate steps be taken to curb the slaughter.\nWhen this day comes, patience with drunken driving, with\nunsafe vehicles, with repeated offenses, and with flagrant\nviolations of speed and safety laws will end.\nu\u00bb Then, the American people will grow up and take driving\nseriously, and reduce the number of tragic deaths of child\nren and adults alike many of whom die through no\nfault of their own, only to have society do comparatively\nnothing to punish their killer.\nThe State Board of Conservation says that stone crabs\nmust measure four inches in length of claw before they are\nlegal to keep. Females must not be taken.\nBy the time a man is fixed for life he has about worried\nhimself to death.\n_ THE BENDS\nI^-\u2014 c IJ. _ '^l\no# if\nR-'Wi\nYou can count on her\ni -to be of service j\nTHE AMERICAN WAY\nI can <wr\nf MONO WITHOUT 1\nI YOU\u2014 J\ny\nC\" I^l .1\nZ-BuT WHE\u00a3e\\ A\nARE YOU 60W6 I\nI TO BE WITHOUT I j\nj\nA' >X SI SI\nUI V\nHe Hadn\u2019t Thought of That!\nAn\nEXTRA I\nOFFICE I\nTELEPHONE I\ni ncreases\nefficiency\n\"Tv I\nIt\u2019s easy to see that an extra telephone or two in\nthis office would help everyone to work more I\nefficiently.\nAre you losing valuable time in your office?\nMr hy not call our business service department.\nWe 11 be delighted to help you develop a more\nworkable telephone plan\nCall by th* Telephone Office for your\nfor lilting LONG DISTANCE Telephone numbers\nQuincy Telephone Co.\nSERVING THIS AREA SINCE 1898\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, MARCH 6, 1953\nMeikrowaves\nPollsters seem to come up with\nall the answers these days\nfrom sex to politics and to\nkeep pace, the only answer seems\nto be \u201cjoin \u2019em.\u201d\nThe professional pollsters go\nto a lot of trouble to find \u201crep\nresentative samples\u201d of opinion\non which to base their predic\ntions.\nWith this in mind, I launched\na new poll the othier day. The\nquestion, \u201cDo you know the\nnames of the State Cabinet of\nficers?\u201d\nJust to be fair about it, I sta\ntioned myself in downtown Tal\nlahassee just about hollering\ndistance from the snow white\nbuildings of the Capitol Center.\nPhrasing of the question itself\nalso was carefully considered\nand emphasis was put on \u201cState\u201d\nto avoid confusion among some\nTallahasseeans, who having liv\ned in a dry county so long, might\nquickly rattle off the brands of\nrefreshment currently stocking\ntheir kitchen cabinets.\nOut of my \u201crepresentative\nsample\u201d of 10 people the first\n10 that would stop and talk\none man who had lived in Talla\nhassee all his 65 years and work\ned for the state seven of those\nyears, named all the Cabinet and\nput them in the right job.\nEveryone knew who the Gov\nernor was but some weren\u2019t\nsure about his first name. Most\nknew the names of some Cabinet\nmembers and could place them\nin the right job.\nOnly people who had lived in\nFlorida at least 10 years and\nsaid they voted with some degree\nof regularity were counted.\nOne lady, who was about 65,\nand said she had lived in Tal\nlahassee 18 years and in Florida\nsince she was 18, probably sum\nmed up the sentiment.\n\u201cI just don\u2019t keep up with\nsuch as that. I vote at every\nelection, but I have friends who\nI ask about the candidates.\u201d\nIt\u2019s doubtful that this proves\nanything, but it is interesting\nin view of the upcoming 1960\nelection.\nProbably for the first time in\nmany years there will be a ser\nious campaign for a cabinet post\nmaybe two.\nAlthough he has been written\noff many times in his long ca\nreer, Nathan Mayo, Commission\ner of Agriculture, almost cer\ntainly will retire before 1960\nor at least not seek another term.\nWhether he retires before the\n1960 election apparently will be\nguided by whether the man he\nwants as \u201cheir apparent\u201d will be\nappointed by Gov. Le\u00dfoy Col\nlins to fill the post.\nUnder normal circumstances\nthis would be done.\nPresent speculation as to\nr\n\nI _ 1\nsi\narc\nKA V s\naw I I\njuwrW\u00ab\u00abUf tar tW*\u2022 MrfMvavtantoy-IM Tvri Skilin*\ntittm hm mv ^pMVtvfrr Tku*itrMr4\nIts like getting back 15i on every gas dollar I\nHere\u2019s the biggest savings story of the\nyear! And here\u2019s why.\nIt all starts with Ford\u2019s new dream of a\ndrive called Cruise-O-Matic... the newest,\nmost versatile, most automatic of them all!\nTwo new driving ranges let you choose your\nstarts for the road conditions that exist. For\nexample, in most of the driving you\u2019ll do,\nyou can take off lively as a spring lamb if\nyou wish. And on snow, ice or any slippery\nroad surface, with the extra driving range\nyou can get sure-footed starts that are\nsteady and silky-smooth.\nNow, team this all-new automatic with\nFord\u2019s new Thunderbird-powered V-8\nInman-Johnson Motor Company, Inc.\n324 W. JJEFFERSON ST. QUINCY, FLA.\nFOB A inni BUY IN A USES CAB OB HUCI, BE SUBE TO SEE OUB 01 \u00aeTHEB SELECTIONS\nMayo\u2019s choice is Lee Thompson,\nwho is Mayo\u2019s top aide, and does\nall the heavy work of the job at\npresent.\nThere are rumbles from every\nsphere on other possibilities.\nAmong them W. R. (Buster) Han\ncock, a Tampa fertilizer man,\nwith wide connections in the ag\nriculture field.\nHouse speaker Doyle Conner\nis also interested in the job.\nAlthough there has been talk\nof Secretary of State R. A. Gray\nstepping down, the indications\nare at present that he probably\nwill seek another term.\nThe most frequently mention\ned possibility for this job is\nRep. John Shipp, Marianna text\nbook salesman.\nAll this boils down to the basic\nquestion:\nWill South Florida seize the\nopportunity to elect Cabinet offi\ncers?\nThis question has been one of\nthe basic ingredients during re\napportionment squabbles the last\nfew years with small county\nlegislators pointing to the possi\nbility of ultimate control of the\ngovernor\u2019s office and the cabinet\nposts by the heavily populated\nareas in South Florida.\nSmaller county legislators\nmaintained that apportionment\nfavoring their areas was an es\nsential safeguard to the possibil\nity of big county control of the\nCabinet and governor\u2019s office.\nIf something happens between\nnow and 1960 to unify the\nthoughts of heavily populated\nareas, there might be a cam\npaign based on more representa\ntion for larger counties on the\nCabinet If not, it will prob\nably rock along about as it has\nin years past.\nJust for the record, the Cabi\nnet officers are, er, well: Secre\ntary of State R. A. Gray, At\ntorney General Richard W. Er\nvin, Comptroller Ray Green,\nTreasurer J. Edwin Larson, Sup\nerintendent of Public Instruction\nThomas Bailey, and Commission\ner of Agriculture Nathan Mayo.\nAnother past-time these days\nseems to be figuring out business\ntrends.\nRecently the comptroller\u2019s of\nfice came out with a breakdown\non the sales tax collections by\ntypes of business.\nGenerally overlooked in the\nlearned discussions of the fig\nures were two of great signifi\ncance.\nThe figures involved were total\nsales in junk yards and hat shops.\nJunk yard sales were off 5.19\nper cent and hat shops were off\n6.98 per cent pointing out\nwhat most husbands have long\nsuspected: A close correlation\nbetween junk and women\u2019s hats.\nDon Meiklejohn\n(with up to 300 hp) and you get as much\nas 15% better gas mileage, too! That\u2019s be\ncause a special gas-saving rear axle ratio\nis used to give you all the savings of \u201cbuilt\nin* overdrive economy.\nAnd based on factory suggested retail\ndelivered prices, a Cruise-O-Matic Ford is\npriced lowest of the low-price three with\ncomparable equipment\nSo, with Thunderbird go down-to\nearth gas savings plot Ford\u2019s tradition\nally low prices and high resale return\nyou have the best reasons in the world to\nmake yourself a deal on a beautiful new\nCruise-O-Matic Ford!\nNavy Opens Two\nEnlistee Fields\nLCDR M. R. Smith, officer in\ncharge of Navy recruiting for\nthe states of Florida and Geor\ngia, has just announced that the\nNavy is opening two enlisted\nfields in the Signalman and\nQuartermaster ratings. The lat\nter of the two has been in exis\ntence for many years, however,\nrequirements currently establish\nr any openings in the petty of\nficer ranks for qualified young\nmen.\nThe Signalman and Quarter\nmaster are the ship Navigator\u2019s\nright-hand men. They ar- fa\nmiliar with most phases of nav\nigation, communications, signals\nat sea, semaphore, and many\nother interesting and informa\ntive job categories having to do\nwith \u201crunning a ship at sea\u201d.\n\u201cThis is an opportunity for\nqualified young men to step\ninto the Navy in a field which\nwill assure them travel and the\nWhen you are short of time\nthat\u2019s when a checking\naccount proves its worth!\nNo need to run all over town, burn up gas, spend\ncarfare, use up precious time to pay bills each\nmonth. Why not take just a few minutes soon\nand open a*handy checking account with us?\nYour cancelled checks are your receipts and you\ncan pay all your bills in a matter of minutes, by\nmail. Come in and find out how much easier it is\nto manage money the time-saving \u201ccheck way\u201d!\nThe\nQuincy State Bank\nkind of job that the Navy offers\nyoung men who love the sea,\u201d\nstated Mr. Smith. He further\nstated that these two enlisted\nratings were to be included in\nthe Navy\u2019s famous High School\nGraduate Training program, with\ntwo fleet schools established for\nqualified men to attend.\nInterested young men who\nare interested in these Navy\n\u201cjobs of adventure\u201d should con\u00ae\ntact their nearest Navy Re\ncruiter at Tallahassee, or call\n24222, Tallahassee for informa\ntion.\nON CURBING OIL IMPORTS\nThe Administration acknow\nledged recently that its \u201cvolun\ntary\u201d program for curbing oil\nimports was not solving the\nproblems of this country\u2019s oil\nindustry.\nThe special Cabinet committee\non oil imports, under the chair\nmanship of Sinclair Weeks, Sec\nretary of Commerce, plans a\nmeeting soon to see what can\nbe done.\nCOME IN, ACTION TEST A\nCRUISE-O-MATIC\n58 FORD\nnothing newer in the world\nA","height":"29163","width":"20013"}}
